00:00:26.325 --> 00:00:28.075
EARLL MURMAN: OK, the
title of this module

00:00:28.075 --> 00:00:29.530
is Improving the Enterprise.

00:00:29.530 --> 00:00:31.600
And just to put
it in context, we

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.070
inherited a poorly
performing clinic.

00:00:34.070 --> 00:00:37.390
We have applied lean,
what we call local lean.

00:00:37.390 --> 00:00:39.970
But now we're going
to look at, how

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:42.950
do you handle issues that are
outside the span of control

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:45.310
of the clinic?

00:00:45.310 --> 00:00:47.840
And this is where
you usually end up.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.360
That's the objective for
the rest of the afternoon,

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:51.777
with the exception of the very--

00:00:51.777 --> 00:00:53.360
at very end, we're
going to tee you up

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:54.920
on a homework assignment.

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:57.470
OK, so if you want to
improve the whole enterprise,

00:00:57.470 --> 00:00:58.850
you can't just do it locally.

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:01.280
You'll end up suboptimizing
the enterprise.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:02.720
You may optimize
yourself locally,

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:04.910
but you'll suboptimize
the enterprise.

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:07.610
So we want to work through
on how organizations

00:01:07.610 --> 00:01:11.180
can adapt to external
constraints and implement lean.

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:13.970
And the mode we're
going to do this

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:16.460
is something called a rapid
process improvement workshop,

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:19.280
which is one way to
implement lean across a wider

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.020
group than what you have here.

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:23.270
We're going to look at
including a daily management

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:25.550
system, which is a
little bit of an add-on.

00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:28.490
And then we're going to see we
have some trouble doing that,

00:01:28.490 --> 00:01:30.110
and we'll discuss it.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:34.400
OK, so just to frame this,
health care operations

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:36.110
are often impacted
by decisions which

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:38.080
are outside the
control of the clinic.

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:41.390
I mean, this is
regulations, insurance,

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:43.190
resource constraints.

00:01:43.190 --> 00:01:46.070
We had something
earlier this afternoon,

00:01:46.070 --> 00:01:48.560
where we had some
change of employees.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:51.050
It was beyond the
purview of the clinic.

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:52.820
We had to adjust for that.

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:55.460
That was a disruptive
thing we had to handle,

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:57.560
which is not unusual.

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:00.115
And we need to optimize
at the enterprise level,

00:02:00.115 --> 00:02:00.990
as I've already said.

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:06.187
Otherwise, we may not optimize
across our whole enterprise.

00:02:09.169 --> 00:02:11.540
OK, I think this has
already been contained.

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:14.450
What I'd really like to
do is get some examples

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:15.950
from your own experience.

00:02:15.950 --> 00:02:20.300
Or what are some external
things that you've

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:25.174
experienced that have disrupted
your enterprises you work with?

00:02:25.174 --> 00:02:25.674
Yeah?

00:02:25.674 --> 00:02:29.390
AUDIENCE: Well, just patients
showing up all in one bunch.

00:02:29.390 --> 00:02:32.990
Like when I was on triage
as a medicine resident,

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:37.400
all of our admissions would show
up at 4:30 in the afternoon.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.400
Because everyone was coming
to the ER in the afternoon.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:43.820
And then, by the time
they got worked up,

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:47.870
that load would hit the
medicine admitting team at 4:30.

00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:49.160
So it's kind of the--

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:51.410
EARLL MURMAN: So yeah,
this is a classic thing,

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:53.658
isn't it, that the one
department in the enterprise

00:02:53.658 --> 00:02:54.950
impacting the other department.

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:57.470
And it's out of your control.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:59.100
And of course, yeah, exactly.

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:04.295
And it can happen the other
way, too, that the admissions,

00:03:04.295 --> 00:03:06.170
they're not being admitted
into the hospital.

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:08.990
So they're piling up in the
ER and affecting the ER.

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:10.900
OK.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:11.530
Other things?

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:12.355
Yeah?

00:03:12.355 --> 00:03:13.585
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:13.585 --> 00:03:14.460
EARLL MURMAN: Pardon?

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:15.070
AUDIENCE: Funding.

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:15.700
EARLL MURMAN: Funding.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:17.570
OK, so resources--
here's the thing, where

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:19.780
you know you can do something.

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:22.390
You want to do something, but
you can't get the funding.

00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.400
Or maybe you get the funding,
and then there's a reduction.

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:26.275
I mean, that's happening
in my local hospital

00:03:26.275 --> 00:03:28.390
now in Washington state.

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:33.220
The state's grappling with a $2
billion budget shortfall gap.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:35.470
And they provide
basic health coverage

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:38.650
for underemployed
people in the state.

00:03:38.650 --> 00:03:40.300
I live in a rural community.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:42.130
My hospital has a
lot of these people.

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.050
They're about ready to
lose all that money,

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:46.600
and they still have
to treat the patients.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:47.907
OK.

00:03:47.907 --> 00:03:48.990
It's beyond their control.

00:03:48.990 --> 00:03:50.970
I mean, they can go down to
Olympia and lobby a little bit.

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:53.010
But basically, it's
beyond their control.

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:53.647
Yeah?

00:03:53.647 --> 00:03:55.980
AUDIENCE: So I've been working
on a telephone operations

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:59.190
improvement project recently
with an ancillary department,

00:03:59.190 --> 00:04:01.170
where we only have
three front desk staff.

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.540
And our intervention
was to separate

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:05.550
one of the front
phones in the back area

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:08.133
and then have just the
front desk staff locked

00:04:08.133 --> 00:04:10.050
at the front, directly
interact with patients,

00:04:10.050 --> 00:04:12.480
and not have to worry
about phone calls.

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:17.310
And in doing our pilot, to the
two-week PBSA pilot, some days,

00:04:17.310 --> 00:04:19.660
we only had one staff
actually show up to work.

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:23.625
So obviously, our plan
didn't go as it would have,

00:04:23.625 --> 00:04:25.380
if we had the three staff.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:26.430
EARLL MURMAN: Yeah.

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:28.170
So there you got
an employee issue.

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:29.880
Yeah.

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:31.560
It might have
unreliable employees,

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:34.740
or maybe there are complications
in their family life,

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:36.240
that they couldn't
come or whatever.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:37.430
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] sick.

00:04:37.430 --> 00:04:39.030
EARLL MURMAN: Sick, yeah.

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:40.750
Any other examples?

00:04:40.750 --> 00:04:41.555
Yeah?

00:04:41.555 --> 00:04:43.180
AUDIENCE: The
recession-- our economics

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:45.820
and how it affects our
patients [INAUDIBLE]..

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:48.403
EARLL MURMAN: Yeah, I mean, we
can't control the world, right?

00:04:48.403 --> 00:04:51.040
We're in an environment
imposed on us,

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:52.940
and we have to deal with it.

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:54.150
Yeah.

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:55.400
Any examples you can think of?

00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:56.510
AUDIENCE: Space constraints.

00:04:56.510 --> 00:04:57.843
EARLL MURMAN: Space constraints.

00:04:57.843 --> 00:05:01.490
AUDIENCE: When your capacity
exceeds your [INAUDIBLE]..

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:03.560
EARLL MURMAN: Yeah, just
not enough facilities.

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:06.680
OK, so these are not
unusual disruptions.

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:12.670
OK, so we say this
is a statement.

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:14.620
I suppose it may be
more of a hypothesis.

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:17.560
But the lean organizations,
by their nature,

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:19.870
are maybe more
adaptable to change

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:22.540
than other organizations.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:25.670
First of all, you're
process-oriented.

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:27.490
You think about processes.

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:32.888
You think less about side
or turfs or rice bowls,

00:05:32.888 --> 00:05:33.930
or those kinds of things.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:36.780
You get process-oriented
and think about,

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:38.580
how do you change your process?

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:40.590
If you have standardization,
which you should

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:42.330
if you're a good
lean organization,

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:44.580
it means you're going to
have fewer things to change.

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:46.500
You have a stable base
on which to change,

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:49.650
as opposed to many things
that have to be changed.

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:52.080
You're used to thinking of
things in rapid cycle times.

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:54.870
And that's going to be really
this whole rapid process

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:58.345
improvement workshop,
adapting to change quickly.

00:05:58.345 --> 00:05:59.720
And you just have
a culture where

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:02.420
you're accepting of change.

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:03.202
Lean is a Journey.

00:06:03.202 --> 00:06:04.160
You're always changing.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:05.618
You're always trying
to get better.

00:06:05.618 --> 00:06:07.500
So you're not fearful of change.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:11.960
So these are all things that,
in terms of a lean organization,

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:16.450
help you in dealing with
these external constraints.

00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:19.510
Just to anchor this back in this
process improvement framework

00:06:19.510 --> 00:06:23.080
we've been using-- and by
the way, a copy of this

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:26.130
is in your folders, just
for your reference purposes.

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:28.510
And why we put it
there is to try

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:35.710
to impart a thought process of
structured approach to change

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:37.690
and not ad hoc
approach to change.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:39.708
So this is one
structured approach.

00:06:39.708 --> 00:06:41.500
There are many other
structured approaches.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:44.140
This is one that we adopted,
just to give you one.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:46.390
And right now, we're in here.

00:06:46.390 --> 00:06:48.617
We're going to be doing another.

00:06:48.617 --> 00:06:50.200
We're going to have
some changes we're

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:51.700
going to introduce to you.

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:53.548
They're going to be
beyond your control.

00:06:53.548 --> 00:06:55.090
And we're going to
have to figure out

00:06:55.090 --> 00:06:57.430
how to respond to them,
develop an implementation plan,

00:06:57.430 --> 00:06:58.630
and try it out.

00:06:58.630 --> 00:07:02.095
And in doing this, as you
go beyond your clinic,

00:07:02.095 --> 00:07:03.970
you're going to have to
interact with a wider

00:07:03.970 --> 00:07:05.630
group of stakeholders.

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:07.570
And that's part of
the complexity of it.

00:07:07.570 --> 00:07:11.600
We've heard from Beau, for
example, already about that.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.960
So let's talk a little
bit about stakeholders.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:17.170
We had this slide up yesterday
in a slightly different format.

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.360
But a health care
enterprise like yours

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:20.890
has a lot of stakeholders.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:24.250
And let's just try to identify,
in the interest of time

00:07:24.250 --> 00:07:27.880
and keeping this focus,
for our clinics here,

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:30.028
who are our major stakeholders?

00:07:30.028 --> 00:07:30.820
AUDIENCE: Patients.

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:33.700
EARLL MURMAN: Patients, OK.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:34.330
OK.

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:35.163
AUDIENCE: Suppliers.

00:07:35.163 --> 00:07:37.972
EARLL MURMAN: Suppliers, OK.

00:07:37.972 --> 00:07:38.805
AUDIENCE: Providers.

00:07:38.805 --> 00:07:41.080
AUDIENCE: Providers and
doctors and the medical staff.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.505
EARLL MURMAN: Yeah, so you
have the staff, medical staff.

00:07:43.505 --> 00:07:45.380
Why don't we just put
all the staff together.

00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:48.670
There's the medical
and the administrative.

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:50.260
For now, let's
just call it staff.

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:54.650
Any other stakeholders in our
simulated clinic environment?

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:55.590
AUDIENCE: Investors?

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:57.005
EARLL MURMAN: Investors, OK.

00:08:00.562 --> 00:08:03.010
AUDIENCE: The government.

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:04.120
EARLL MURMAN: OK.

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:06.640
The government is an
important stakeholder,

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.347
but probably not so much for
our classroom environment here.

00:08:10.347 --> 00:08:11.930
But there is another
important-- yeah?

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:13.900
AUDIENCE: Oh,
whoever's regulating.

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:15.358
EARLL MURMAN: We've
got management.

00:08:15.358 --> 00:08:17.290
It's called managers--

00:08:17.290 --> 00:08:21.640
CFO or CMO, or whatever it is.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:23.560
You've got somebody
you're reporting to.

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:25.690
They keep imposing new
things on you and saying,

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:27.040
you can't do this,
you can't do that.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:28.707
AUDIENCE: You've got
the payers as well.

00:08:28.707 --> 00:08:30.760
EARLL MURMAN: Payers, OK.

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:34.710
We haven't actually collected
any money from them yet. .

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:36.312
OK, this is a pretty good group.

00:08:36.312 --> 00:08:37.770
So let's just stay
with that group.

00:08:37.770 --> 00:08:39.789
But you can imagine, in a
more complex enterprise,

00:08:39.789 --> 00:08:41.039
you're going have more people.

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:43.806
You'll have regulators.

00:08:43.806 --> 00:08:47.770
You might have partners.

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:51.160
My hospital, for example,
can't do a number of procedures

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:52.000
as a small hospital.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.040
So partners with
Swedish Hospital,

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:56.500
in Seattle, and Harrison
Hospital, in Bremerton,

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:59.290
these are important
stakeholders; EMS systems.

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:01.960
They're all sorts
of other partners.

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:04.480
Now, we had this slide
up yesterday, too.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:07.990
But each of these stakeholders
expects some value

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:10.010
from your enterprise.

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:12.610
So let's just think,
what value do patients

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:15.960
expect from your clinic?

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:16.710
AUDIENCE: Quality.

00:09:16.710 --> 00:09:17.627
EARLL MURMAN: Quality.

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:24.890
OK, so remember, we've
been doing that managements

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:27.560
ask you, every so often,
did some patient get

00:09:27.560 --> 00:09:29.240
treated incorrectly?

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:31.140
That's a concern
they track that.

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:32.190
AUDIENCE: Affordability.

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:33.250
EARLL MURMAN: Affordability.

00:09:33.250 --> 00:09:33.750
OK.

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:41.880
Maybe we should introduce
a pay for service,

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:44.620
pay for performance
option in this simulation.

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:45.880
We haven't done that yet.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:46.380
OK.

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:47.310
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:48.490
AUDIENCE: Quick access?

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:49.590
EARLL MURMAN: Access, yep.

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:55.080
Access-- they want
to get treated.

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:56.078
AUDIENCE: The time.

00:09:56.078 --> 00:09:56.870
EARLL MURMAN: Time?

00:09:56.870 --> 00:09:57.495
AUDIENCE: Time.

00:09:57.495 --> 00:09:58.580
EARLL MURMAN: Time.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:00.810
OK.

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:03.000
That's a metric
we've been tracking.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.530
AUDIENCE: Safety [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:05.250
Safety.

00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:06.818
EARLL MURMAN: Safety.

00:10:06.818 --> 00:10:08.610
Yeah, it's a little
bit related to quality,

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:11.350
but we'll put it here.

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:13.000
OK, how about the suppliers?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.670
What are they?

00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:17.800
And by the way, also,
this is a two-way street.

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:22.170
I mean, they expect value,
and you expect value.

00:10:22.170 --> 00:10:25.080
Suppliers-- what are some
of the value considerations

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:26.430
that come in with suppliers?

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:28.336
AUDIENCE: Accuracy?

00:10:28.336 --> 00:10:29.940
You got the order accuracy.

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:33.025
EARLL MURMAN: Accuracy, OK.

00:10:33.025 --> 00:10:33.900
AUDIENCE: Timeliness.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:36.024
EARLL MURMAN: Timeliness.

00:10:36.024 --> 00:10:38.160
AUDIENCE: Cost.

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:38.952
EARLL MURMAN: Cost.

00:10:38.952 --> 00:10:41.580
And what do you expect
from your suppliers?

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:43.955
What value do you expect to get?

00:10:43.955 --> 00:10:44.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:44.830 --> 00:10:45.310
AUDIENCE: Quality.

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:46.227
EARLL MURMAN: Quality.

00:10:49.390 --> 00:10:54.970
AUDIENCE: Reliability,
in both ways, I guess,

00:10:54.970 --> 00:11:00.010
that they rely on a
steady stream of orders.

